node.text:
This week, NASA confirmed that Arabia Terra, an area of northern Mars, was once the site of immense volcanic activity as thousands of “super eruptions” exploded over a period of 500 million years.

The basins left in their wake were previously thought to have been depressions left by asteroid strikes to the Martian surface. However, it now appears that they are the scars of volcanic explosions which tore through the Martian surface around 4 billion years ago.

Image credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/University of Arizona

node.text:
Because queens come in all shapes and sizes, a dazzling soldier fly has been named after RuPaul. Opaluma rupaul was crowned so in honor of its "costume of shiny metallic rainbow colours" resembling drag costumes and the "charisma and uniqueness" that lights up the bug community.

Dr. Bryan Lessard of Australia's National Research Collections hopes the news will shine a spotlight on Australia’s insect diversity, particularly those species affected by the Black Summer bushfires in 2019 and 2020.

“Many of the thirteen new soldier flies I named are from areas impacted by the Black Summer bushfires,” Dr Lessard said. “Soldier flies are valuable in the ecosystem. The larvae recycle nutrients from dead plants and animals, while adults are pollinators of some Australian plants.”

Sashay away, O rupaul.
​
​Image credit: Bryan Lessard, CSIRO

The climate crisis is unfolding around us with extreme weather events becoming more common and living organisms having to survive or perish in a changing world. In this episode, host Dr Alfredo Carpineti sat down with Dr Alexandre Kōberle, a research fellow at the Grantham Institute for Climate Change, to discuss how we got here, how we can avoid the worse case scenarios, what political will is needed, and if there are ways to actually fix the mess we are in? 

You can listen to this episode of IFLScience: The Big Questions and subscribe to the podcast on all your favorite podcast apps, or hit this video via the link in our bio for direct links.

Happy #OzoneDay! Today we raise awareness of the critical role of the ozone layer in our survival on planet Earth. It makes the planet inhabitable by forming a thin gaseous shield around the globe that protects it from the Sun's harmful rays.

The day is used to remind governments, corporations and individuals to do their part to maintain the ozone in opting for lower-emission and carbon neutral technologies, as well as making every day changes to reduce our negative influence on its stability. 

In 2021, the hole that emerges in Earth's ozone layer annually has been found to be unusually large, encompassing an area larger than Antarctica, according to the Copernicus Atmosphere Monitoring Service (CAMS).

Using satellite and in situ observations, researchers at CAMS have found that the hole in the ozone layer above the South Pole has grown considerably in the last fortnight after a sluggish start to the season and is now larger than 75 percent of ozone holes at this time of the year since 1979.

Hit the image post via the link in our bio to read the full story 📖

​Video credit: NASA/GSFC

Take a moment to check out these jaw-dropping, prize-winning aerial shots from the Drone Photo competition from the Siena Awards 2021!
​ 
“Labyrinth of Time” by Tomáš Neuwirth. A digital collage created by photographing a labyrinth during two seasons.
​ 
“Mitosis” by Siman Laszlo. When lakes freeze at winter we can look for ice-stars on the surface. This year Siman was lucky to experience this.
​
“The Eye of the Volcano” by Bjorn Kristjansson. Note the silver textures of the lava that has recently been ejected high up in the air in series of pulses, which originated from around 100 to 200 meters depth underneath the crater.
​
“Tailing Dam Abstract” by David Dahlenburg. This image was captured over a copper, gold and uranium mine in a remote location in South Australia. The dam contains by products from the mining process. The colours and texture that are created look truly of another world.
​
“Sheep in Congress” by Yoel Robert Assiag, who said: In the north of Israel, I documented during summer and winter a herd of 1500 sheep which became more than 1900 heads.
​
Drone Awards is the most important worldwide competition about aerial photography and video. It’s a project of Siena Awards, dedicated to a different photographic genre deliberately separated from being compared to traditional photography.

node.text:
It's possibly the most metal headline we've had the joy of writing, but be confident that no one is planning to sacrifice brave explorers to build cities on other worlds. (It still sounds a lot like space vampires, though.)

Transporting heavy materials into Earth's orbit is horrendously expensive, let alone longer journeys. One estimate puts the cost of getting a brick to Mars at $2 million. Prices will presumably fall, but the motivation to use locally sourced materials is obvious.

Mars has plenty of regolith (loose rocks and soil) that could provide the bulk of future building materials but lacks an obvious binding agent. A paper in Materials Today Bio explores the possibility of getting what is needed from astronauts' own bodies, noting that while “you can't get blood from a stone,” you can get its proteins into one.

First author Dr Aled Roberts of the University of Manchester and colleagues combined human serum albumin (HSA) with the closest Earth counterparts to Martian and lunar dust. The result is a material they called AstroCrete. AstroCrete can resist 25 megapascals of compression, right in the middle of the range of concretes used on Earth, and easily sufficient for low Martian gravity.
​
​If you'd like to read more about the future blood cities of Mars, hit this image via the link in our bio. 🔴

Caption this!

This tarsier’s sleepy eyes are the largest eyes of any mammal in relation to their body size. Each eyeball is on average 16mm in diameter and weighs almost as much as the animal's brain.

Found in countries across Southeast Asia, tarsiers are small creatures weighing just 80 to 150g and have soft, fluffy fur. 

Impressively, they can turn their head 180 degrees in each direction thanks to specially adapted vertebrae. You’ve got no chance of sneaking up on these guys.

Meet the dark and mysterious Ayam Cemani, poultry’s answer to Tim Burton and a rare breed of chicken from Indonesia. Thought to have originated from Java, its name is derived from the Indonesian word ayam which means "chicken” and the Javanese word cemani which roughly translates to "thoroughly black".

Known affectionately across the internet as Goth Chicken (or the “Lamborghini of poultry”), this bird’s badass plumage is the result of a dominant gene that causes hyperpigmentation (fibromelanosis). The aesthetic result turns Ayam Cemani’s feathers, beak, internal organs, and even their meat and bones mostly black.

Image credit: F. Xavier Cirer Miro / im2021 / Shutterstock.com

Happy #UnderwaterWednesday! This unusual chap is a Ctenophore, also known as a comb jellyfish. It has eight rows of ciliated combs down the bottom of its body and very lengthy tentacles emerging from thick tentacle sheaths.

Ctenophores are most often found in the bathypelagic zone, a layer of the ocean that sits at a depth of 3,000 to 13,000 feet. It’s frequently referred to as “The Midnight Zone” because of the lack of light at these depths.

Image credit: NOAA
